{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Har nafas Iqbal tera aah mein mastoor hai\" (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, ch. 10), the \"self-address\" is the voice of \"The Muslim\"—Iqbal's idealized inner self or the eternal Muslim spirit—which first rebukes Iqbal for his laments, despair, and fixation on the past,[^1] then proclaims its own timeless role as bearer of divine truth (Tauheed), guardian of existence, and confident herald of future victory.[^2]\n\nThis address culminates in optimism: the Muslim sees the past as a mirror for tomorrow, foreseeing renewal \"from a hidden tumult\" amid the storms of history.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 10 (\"Har nafas Iqbal tera aah mein mastoor hai\"), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/10-har-nafas-iqbal-tera-aah-mein-mastoor-hai/translation/#p-489986).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 10 (\"Har nafas Iqbal tera aah mein mastoor hai\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/10-har-nafas-iqbal-tera-aah-mein-mastoor-hai/translation/#p-6ef7a5).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 10 (\"Har nafas Iqbal tera aah mein mastoor hai\"), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/10-har-nafas-iqbal-tera-aah-mein-mastoor-hai/translation/#p-7c3704).",
